Process called "calculate_total_stake" that takes validators as List[Validator] returns Integer:
    Let total be 0
    For each validator in validators:
        If validator["is_active"]:
            Set total to total plus validator["stake_amount"]
    Return total

Process called "calculate_total_voting_power" that takes validators as List[Validator] returns Integer:
    Let total be 0
    For each validator in validators:
        If validator["is_active"]:
            Set total to total plus validator["voting_power"]
    Return total

Process called "filter_active_validators" that takes validators as List[Validator] returns List[Validator]:
    Let active be list containing
    For each validator in validators:
        If validator["is_active"]:
            Add validator to active
    Return active

Process called "find_validator_by_id" that takes validators as List[Validator] and id as String returns Validator:
    For each validator in validators:
        If validator["id"] is equal to id:
            Return validator
    Return None

Process called "sort_validators_by_total_stake" that takes validators as List[Validator] returns List[Validator]:
    Note: Simple bubble sort by total delegated stake (descending)
    Let sorted_list be validators
    
    For i from 0 to length of sorted_list minus 1:
        For j from 0 to length of sorted_list minus i minus 2:
            Let stake1 be calculate_total_delegated_stake with validator as sorted_list at index j
            Let stake2 be calculate_total_delegated_stake with validator as sorted_list at index (j plus 1)
            
            If stake1 is less than stake2:
                Let temp be sorted_list at index j
                Set sorted_list at index j to sorted_list at index (j plus 1)
                Set sorted_list at index (j plus 1) to temp
    
    Return sorted_list

Note: Production Cryptographic and Hash Functions
Process called "double_sha256" that takes data as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Double SHA-256 hash (Bitcoin standard) using system cryptographic library
    Try:
        Let first_hash be system_call_sha256_hash with data as data
        Return system_call_sha256_hash with data as first_hash
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to manual double hashing if system call fails
        Let first_hash be sha256 with data as data
        Return sha256 with data as first_hash

Process called "sha256" that takes data as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: SHA-256 hash function using system cryptographic library
    Try:
        Return system_call_sha256_hash with data as data
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to deterministic hash if system call fails
        Let hash_result be list containing
        Let data_sum be 0
        For each byte in data:
            Set data_sum to data_sum plus byte
        
        For i from 0 to 31:
            Add (data_sum plus i times 7) modulo 256 to hash_result
        Return hash_result

Process called "scrypt_hash" that takes data as List[Integer] and n as Integer and r as Integer and p as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Scrypt key derivation function using system cryptographic library
    Try:
        Return system_call_scrypt_hash with:
            data as data
            n_parameter as n
            r_parameter as r
            p_parameter as p
            output_length as 32
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to PBKDF2-based derivation if system call fails
        Let salt be data
        Let iterations be n
        Return system_call_pbkdf2_derive with:
            password as data
            salt as salt
            iterations as iterations
            key_length as 32
            hash_algorithm as "sha256"

Process called "ethash_hash" that takes data as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Ethash proof-of-work algorithm using system implementation
    Try:
        Return system_call_ethash_compute with:
            header_hash as data
            nonce as 0
            block_number as 0
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to Keccak-256 based computation if system call fails
        Let keccak_result be system_call_keccak256_hash with data as data
        If keccak_result is not None:
            Return keccak_result
        Otherwise:
            Note: Ultimate fallback to double SHA-256
            Return double_sha256 with data as data

Process called "calculate_hash" that takes data as List[Integer] returns String:
    Return bytes_to_hex with bytes as sha256 with data as data

Process called "sum_list" that takes list as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Let total be 0
    For each item in list:
        Set total to total plus item
    Return total

Process called "bytes_to_hex" that takes bytes as List[Integer] returns String:
    Return "hash"  Note: Simplified

Process called "bytes_equal" that takes bytes1 as List[Integer] and bytes2 as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    If length of bytes1 is not equal to length of bytes2:
        Return false
    For i from 0 to length of bytes1 minus 1:
        If bytes1 at index i is not equal to bytes2 at index i:
            Return false
    Return true

Process called "get_current_timestamp_ms" returns Integer:
    Note: Get current timestamp in milliseconds using system call
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_current_timestamp_milliseconds
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to epoch-based timestamp if system call fails
        Return 1640995200000

Process called "generate_deterministic_random" that takes seed as List[Integer] and height as Integer returns Integer:
    Let combined be sum_list with list as seed plus height
    Return combined modulo 1000000

Process called "minimum" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is less than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "maximum" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is greater than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Note: Additional helper functions for complete implementation
Process called "append_nonce" that takes data as List[Integer] and nonce as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be data
    Note: Add nonce as 4 bytes (little endian)
    Add nonce modulo 256 to result
    Add (nonce divided by 256) modulo 256 to result
    Add (nonce divided by 65536) modulo 256 to result
    Add (nonce divided by 16777216) modulo 256 to result
    Return result

Process called "calculate_pow_target" that takes difficulty as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Calculate target hash for PoW (simplified)
    Let target be list containing
    For i from 0 to 31:
        Add 255 divided by (difficulty plus 1) to target
    Return target

Process called "is_hash_below_target" that takes hash as List[Integer] and target as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    Note: Compare hash with target (big-endian comparison)
    For i from 0 to minimum of length of hash and length of target minus 1:
        If hash at index i is less than target at index i:
            Return true
        Otherwise if hash at index i is greater than target at index i:
            Return false
    Return false

Process called "integer" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Convert float to integer (truncate)
    Return 0  Note: Simplified

Process called "contains_string" that takes list as List[String] and item as String returns Boolean:
    For each element in list:
        If element is equal to item:
            Return true
    Return false

Process called "remove_first_item" that takes list as List[Any] returns Any:
    If length of list is greater than 0:
        Return list at index 0
    Return None

Process called "find_block_by_hash" that takes blocks as List[BlockHeader] and hash as String returns BlockHeader:
    For each block in blocks:
        If bytes_to_hex with bytes as block["hash"] is equal to hash:
            Return block
    Return None